Okay, so they (the n_eff samples) get bigger at first as you increase the warm-up size. I am starting at the default of 500 for the warm-up size. So, fewer warm up samples means there is more guessing for STAN, leading to a relatively higher n_eff by comparison. That makes a lot of sense! Once the warm-up gets toooo small, stan doesnt know what do to! Too much autocorrelation and stan cannot determine your step wise. Then if the warm-up gets too large, you regrow that n_eff because it is very costly in terms of time it takes.
